  </subsection>

  <subsection><title>Logarithm Laws</title>
  <p> 
    In <xref ref="sec-exp-intro"/>, we reviewed the main exponent laws that help us simplify and re-write exponential expressions in simpler ways. 
    Logarithmic expressions also have a similar set of laws that help us re-write logarithmic expressions:
  </p> 

  <assemblage><title>Logarithm Laws</title>
    <p>
      For any postitive numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> the following is true:
    </p>
    <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p> Product Law:
          <md number="yes" xml:id="log-law-product">
            \ln(xy) = \ln x + \ln y 
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p> Quotient Law:
          <md number="yes" xml:id="log-law-quotient">
            \ln\left(\frac{x}{y}\right) = \ln x - \ln y 
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p> Power Law:
          <md number="yes" xml:id="log-law-power">
            \ln\left(x^y\right) = y\ln x 
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage>

<p>
  Similar Laws are also true for other logarithms (with other bases) but we will focus on <m>\ln x</m> (with base <m>e</m>).
</p>

<p>
  <alert> Notation:</alert> The notation <m>\ln x^y</m> means <m>\ln\left(x^y\right)</m>. 
  If the intent is to rais the entire logarithm to a power, we would write <m>\left(\ln x\right)^y</m>. 
  You should never write <m>\ln^a(x)</m> (it does not mean anything).
</p>

<p>
It is important to understand these laws, and it is also important to understand some common errors to avoid when applying these laws:
</p> 

 <assemblage><title>Common Errors</title>
    <p>
      Be careful to not apply `rules' that are not true. For example, note that:
    </p>
    <p>
    <men xml:id="log-error1">
      \ln (x \pm y) \neq \ln x \pm \ln y
    </men>
    <men>
      (\ln x)^a \neq a(\ln x)
    </men>
    <men>
      a\ln x + b\ln y \neq ab\ln\left(xy\right) 
    </men>
     <men>
      \ln\left(xy\right) \neq \ln\left(x\right) \ln\left(y\right) 
    </men>   
  </p>
  </assemblage>

  <example><title>True or False</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Suppose <m>a, b,</m> and <m>c</m> are positive numbers.  
        Which of the following are true, and which are false? 
      </p>
      <p>
      Note: For a statement involving <m>a, b,</m> and/or <m>c</m> to be true, it must be true for ALL positive numbers <m>a, b,</m> and <m>c</m>. 
      </p>
      <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ln (6) + \ln(4.5)=\ln (27)</m> 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ln (5x) =\ln (5)\ln (x)</m> 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ln \left(\frac{a}{bc}\right)=\ln a - \ln b - \ln c</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
          <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\boxed{\mbox{TRUE}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\boxed{\mbox{FALSE}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\boxed{\mbox{TRUE}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>

      </answer>
    <solution>
          <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
           Using <xref ref="log-law-product"/> (uing it `backwards'), we see that <m>\ln (6) + \ln(4.5)=\ln (6\cdot 4.6) = \ln (27)</m>. 
           So the statement is <m>\boxed{\mbox{TRUE}}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ln (5x) =\ln (5)\ln (x)</m>. This is precisely one of the common errors. The statement is <m>\boxed{\mbox{FALSE}}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            First we use <xref ref="log-law-quotient"/>:
            <md>
              \ln \left(\frac{a}{bc}\right)=\ln a - \ln (bc)
            </md>
            Then we use <xref ref="log-law-product"/> on the second term:
                        <md>
              \ln \left(\frac{a}{bc}\right)=\ln a - \ln (bc) = \ln a - (\ln b + \ln c) = \ln a - \ln b - \ln c
            </md>
            So the statement is <m>\boxed{\mbox{TRUE}}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

<exercise><title>True or False? - HOMEMADE</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      (Not randomizable)
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Numeric");
      $a = random(3,6,1);
      $ans = Compute("$a*x^($a-1)");
$popup1 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],1);
$popup2 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],1);
$popup3 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],2);
$popup4 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],1);
$popup5 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],2);
$popup6 = PopUp(['?','True','False'],1);

      Context()->functions->disable('All');
      Context()->functions->enable('sqrt');
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
       <p>
      Suppose <m>a, b, c,</m> and <m>x</m> are positive numbers.  
        Which of the following statements are true, and which are false? 
      </p>
      <p>
      Note: For a statement involving <m>a, b,c,</m> and/or <m>x</m> to be true, it must be true for ALL positive numbers <m>a, b,</m> and <m>c</m>. 
      </p>
<p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\ln (48)-\ln (3) = \ln (16)</m> <var name="$popup1" form="popup"/>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\ln a + \ln b + \ln c=\ln (abc)</m> <var name="$popup2" form="popup"/>
      </p>
    </li>
        <li>
      <p>
        <m>\ln (105)-\ln (40) = \ln (65)</m> <var name="$popup3" form="popup"/> 
      </p>
    </li>
        <li>
      <p>
        <m>3a\ln (x+2)=\ln (x+2)^{3a}</m> <var name="$popup4" form="popup"/> 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\ln (7x^3)=3\ln 7x</m> <var name="$popup5" form="popup"/> 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\ln(\sqrt[3]{5})=\frac{1}{3}\ln (5)</m> <var name="$popup6" form="popup"/> 
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
</exercise>

  <example><title>Write as one logarithm</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Write each of the following expressions as a single logarithm, with no coefficient. 
      </p>
      <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>2 \ln 8 - 5 \ln 2</m> 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>5\ln (x-2) - \ln (x+5)+3\ln x</m> 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
          <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>2 \ln 8 - 5 \ln 2 = \boxed{\ln 2}</m> 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>5\ln (x-2) - \ln (x+5)+3\ln x = \boxed{\ln \left(\frac{(x-2)^5x^3}{x+5}\right)}</m> 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
      </answer>
    <solution>
          <p>
            Let's use the logarithm laws several times, and be careful to not use `false laws':
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>2 \ln 8 - 5 \ln 2 = \ln 8^2 - \ln 2^5 = \ln \left(\frac{8^2}{2^5} \right) = \ln \left(\frac{64}{32} \right) = \boxed{\ln 2} </m> 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>5\ln (x-2) - \ln (x+5)+3\ln x = \ln (x-2)^5 + \ln (x+5)^{-1}+\ln x^3 = \ln \left((x-2)^5(x+5)^{-1}x^3\right) = \boxed{\ln \left(\frac{(x-2)^5x^3}{x+5}\right)}  </m> 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

<exercise><title>Write as one logarithm - HOMEMADE</title>
    <introduction>
    <p>
      (Not randomizable)
    </p>
  </introduction>
    <webwork>
      <pg-code>
        Context("LimitedRadical");
        $a = Formula("4");
        Context("LimitedRadical");
        $b = Formula("16");
        Context("Numeric");
        $c = Formula("x(x+1)");
        Context("Numeric");
        $d = Formula("x^5");
      </pg-code>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write each of the following expressions as a single logarithm, with no coefficient. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                 <m>\ln 12 + \ln 2 - \ln 6 = \ln A</m>  where <m>A=</m> <var name="$a" width="10"/>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>2\ln 8 + \ln 9 - \ln 36 = \ln B</m>  where <m>B=</m> <var name="$b" width="10"/>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>2\ln (x+1) + \ln x - \ln (x^2-1) = \ln C</m>  where <m>C=</m> <var name="$c" width="10"/>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\frac{1}{2}\ln x^4 - 3\ln x + \ln x^6 = \ln D</m>  where <m>D=</m> <var name="$d" width="10"/>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </webwork>
  </exercise>

